## Motion Animation Library

### MCP Integration

Motion provides MCP tools for generating professional CSS easing functions:

- **Generate CSS Spring Animations**: Use `mcp_motion_generate-css-spring` to create spring-based animations
  - Parameters:
    - `bounce`: Number between 0 and 1 (0 = no bounce, 1 = max bounce). Default: 0.2
    - `duration`: Perceptual duration in seconds. Default: 0.4
  - Returns: CSS `<duration> <easing-function>` string for use in CSS transitions
  - Example: Quick animations ~0.2s, normal ~0.3-0.4s, slow ~1s
- **Generate CSS Bounce Easing**: Use `mcp_motion_generate-css-bounce-easing` for bouncing animations
  - Parameters:
    - `duration`: Duration in seconds. Default: 1
  - Best used with longer durations (~1 second) for realistic bounce effects
  - Returns: CSS easing function string

### When to Use Motion MCP Tools

- Use MCP tools when you need CSS-based easing functions for `transition` properties
- For React component animations, use Motion's JavaScript API directly (`motion` components)
- MCP tools are ideal for coordinating CSS transitions with other Motion animations

## Architecture & Separation of Concerns

### Directory Structure

```
src/
  app/           # Next.js App Router pages and layouts
  lib/           # Utility functions and helpers
  components/    # Reusable React components
    ui/          # shadcn/ui components (auto-generated)
public/          # Static assets
hooks/           # Custom React hooks (if needed, typically in src/)
```

### Component Hierarchy

- **Pages** (`src/app/page.tsx`): Route handlers and page-level logic
- **Layouts** (`src/app/layout.tsx`): Shared layout structure
- **Feature Components** (`src/components/`): Domain-specific components
- **UI Components** (`src/components/ui/`): shadcn base components
- **Utilities** (`src/lib/`): Pure functions, helpers

### Rules

- Pages should only handle routing and data fetching
- Business logic belongs in components or custom hooks
- Pure utility functions go in `src/lib/` directory
- UI components are reusable and composable
- No direct DOM manipulation - use React patterns
- Keep components small and focused (< 200 lines when possible)

## Best Practices

### TypeScript

- Use strict type checking
- Define proper interfaces/types for all props
- Avoid `any` - use `unknown` if type is truly unknown
- Use type inference where appropriate
- Export types alongside components when reusable

### React & Next.js

- Use Server Components by default, Client Components only when needed (`"use client"`)
- Implement proper error boundaries
- Use Next.js Image component for all images
- Leverage Next.js metadata API for SEO
- Use proper loading and error states
- Implement proper accessibility (ARIA labels, semantic HTML)

### Styling

- Use Tailwind utility classes - avoid custom CSS when possible
- Follow mobile-first responsive design
- Use CSS variables for theme colors (already configured)
- Maintain consistent spacing scale
- Support dark mode (use `dark:` prefix)

### Code Quality

- Write self-documenting code with clear naming
- Keep functions pure when possible
- Extract magic numbers/strings to constants
- Follow ESLint and Prettier rules for consistent code style

### Code Formatting & Linting

- **ESLint**: Configured with Next.js ESLint config and integrated with Prettier
